Installation Instructions
=========================

This project contains a C implementation of the zeroLET analysis and evaluation
programs. The generated experiment results are written to the `data_c`
directory.


Requirements
------------

Install a C11-compatible C compiler.

On Linux, GCC is sufficient:

    sudo apt install build-essential

On Windows, use MinGW-w64 GCC, MSYS2 GCC, or another compiler that supports C11.

Python is not required to run the C evaluations. It is only needed for the
optional PNG plotting helper:

    pip install pandas matplotlib


Build
-----

From the repository root, build the serial runtime evaluator:

    gcc -std=c11 -Wall -Wextra -O2 analysis_zero_let.c evaluation_zero_let.c -lm -o evaluation_zero_let_c

Build the extremes evaluator:

    gcc -std=c11 -Wall -Wextra -O2 -DZEROLET_EVALUATION_NO_MAIN analysis_zero_let.c evaluation_zero_let.c extremes_zero_let.c -lm -o extremes_zero_let_c

On Linux, you can also build the pthread-based parallel runtime evaluator:

    gcc -std=c11 -Wall -Wextra -O2 evaluation_zero_let_linux_parallel.c analysis_zero_let.c -lm -pthread -o evaluation_zero_let_linux_parallel


Basic Test
----------

Run a small serial runtime evaluation:

    ./evaluation_zero_let_c 3 3 1

On Windows, if your compiler emits `.exe` files, run:

    .\evaluation_zero_let_c.exe 3 3 1

The program should print progress for `n=3` and finish by reporting output files
similar to:

    Results saved to data_c/data_zero_let_RC_n3_1_<seed>_<timestamp>.csv
    Runtime plot saved to data_c/zero_let_Runtime_n3_1_<seed>_<timestamp>.svg
    Normalized runtime plot saved to data_c/zero_let_RC_n3_1_<seed>_<timestamp>.svg

This confirms that the code compiled successfully, ran the zeroLET evaluation,
measured runtime over complexity, and produced both CSV data and SVG plots.


Paper Reproduction Commands
---------------------------

To reproduce the Table IV extremes evaluation:

    ./extremes_zero_let_c 2 12 3

To reproduce the Figure 8 parallel runtime evaluation on Linux:

    ./evaluation_zero_let_linux_parallel 3 10 100

These larger experiments can take significantly longer than the basic test.
